<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1908-12-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1908-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="398" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d398">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2126/351.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Minister <persName type="to">Furniss</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908-12-07"><hi rend="italic">December 7,
                                1908</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Mr. Bacon informs Mr. Furniss that the supplementary telegram of December
                            5 was not intended to limit the good offices of the United States to
                            Europeans, as temporary protection will be cheerfully extended as far as
                            practicable to citizens of any friendly State not having naval vessels
                            at hand. Mr. Furniss is instructed to show this to the senior American
                            naval officer.</p>
